name: Circulation - Fetal
contents:
Circulation

  • Oxygenated blood is provided via the UMBILICAL VEIN (UV) (pO2 4.7kPa, sats 80-90%)
  • and so the fetus is hypoxaemic when compared to the mother.
  • 60% of blood flow bypasses the liver in the Ductus Venosus (DV) which JOINS venous blood from the body and → IVC
  • Eustachean valve (Crista dividens):
  • at junction of IVC and RA streams the highly oxygenated blood across the Foramen Ovale (FO) and into the LA (sats 65%)
  • Majority of the LV blood is delivered to the brain (head/neck) and coronary circulation
  • via the Aorta pO2 2.7
  • The blood returning to the RA from the superior vena cava is even more deoxygenated, with sats of ~25%, because of the relatively high oxygen extraction of the brain.
  • makes sense for this blood to return to the placental circulation via as direct a route as possible (eustachean valve) separates:
  • oxygenated (streams over to LA)
  • deoxygenated - straight over to descending aorta (distal to carotids) via RV and ductus arteriosus.

Cardiac Output

  • CO in the foetus is regarded as the total output of both ventricles = combined ventricular output
  • 45% goes to placental circulation
  • 8% enters pulmonary circulation
  • Due to high PVR + ductus arteriosus, most RV output passes into the arch of the aorta just distal to the origin of the arteries to the head and upper limbs
question2: What happens at birth? Neonatal circulation
contents2:
• At birth cessation of placental flow following the clamping of the cord is accompanied by a rapid and dramatic reduction in PVR as breathing commences.
  • This reduction in PVR and PA pressure allows more blood to flow through the lungs
  • thus increasing the volume of blood (and therefore pressure) in the LA above that of the RA. (LA > RA)
  • these changes result in the closure of the FO so that right heart outflow now passes through the lungs and the left heart as in in the adult circulation.
  • The pressure in the aorta increases as the umbilical vessels are clamped resulting in an increased SVR and:
  • reverse flow from the HIGH PRESSURE AORTA to the, now LOW PA pressure system, via the patent ductus arteriosus.
  • ductus arteriosus goes from allowing blood to flow from higher pressure RV + Lung mix (higher pressures because lungs not in use) to
  • ductus arteriosus NOT allowing blood from RV + lungs to Aorta - because now Aorta pressures > Pulmonary


The patency of the ductus arteriosus is maintained by the low oxygen tension and the vasodilating effects of prostaglandin E2.


DV and DA become anatomically closed 2-3 weeks after birth, although functional closure occurs within hours.


  • Ductus arteriosus - accelerate ductus arteriosus closure,
  • Oxygen,
  • bradykinins and
  • prostaglandin antagonists (e.g. indomethacin)
  • Ductus arteriosus - keep it open
  • PGE1 (e.g. alprostdil) and
  • conditions causing a raised pulmonary vascular resistance such as cold and acidosis help to keep it open.


It is important therefore to keep neonates warm, oxygenated and hydrated (warm, wet and pink) to prevent their

reverting to a fetal circulation, which can be disastrous as they obviously no

longer have the ability to oxygenate themselves via a placenta
contents3:
Tocolytics are agents which decrease uterine tone. Tocolytics include:

  • (1) β -agonists
  • (2) Ca -channel antagonists
  • (3) COX Inhibitors
  • (4) MgSO
  • (5) Nitrates
  • (6) Volatile anaesthetic agents

All tocolytics are discussed in more detail elsewhere - this covers just the mechanism of action of their uterine effects
contents4:
Prostanoids are a diverse family of eicosanoids (20-carbon molecules), produced from arachidonic acid, and include:

Prostanoids:

  • Prostaglandins act as chemical messengers at the site where they are synthesised; cause:
  • Inflammation response
  • Prostaglandins = vasodilatation (specifically renal) except PGFɑ
  • Uterine contraction
  • Inhibit acid synthesis and increase secretion of protective GI mucous
  • Increase renal blood flow
  • Contraction of SM including bronchi
  • Thromboxane = is produced by platelets.  It is a vasoconstrictor and a potent platelet aggregator. (TXA)
  • Prostacyclin - PGI2 - is a vasodilator and prevents the formation of a platelet plug in primary haemostasis.  (PGI)


****CHECK THESE*****

Prostaglandin. (see Renal Blood flow)

PGI2

  • Vascular: vasodilation (renal and pulmonary),
  • platelet aggregation 
  • Prostacyclin (PGI2) → inhibits platelet aggregation, vasodilation

The "E" series of prostaglandins

  • PGE2 EP1 Gq Effects:
  • Respiratory: Bronchoconstriction,
  • GIT Increased contraction
  • Renal: vasodilation (afferent arterioles)
  • PGE2 EP2 Gs Effects:
  • Respiratory: Bronchodilatation,
  • Vascular: maintaining openness of ductus arteriosus
  • GIT : decreased contraction
  • Renal: vasodilatation (afferent arterioles)
  • PGE2 EP3 Gi Effects:
  • GIT : gastric mucous production, GIT contraction
  • Uterine contraction.

PGFɑ

  • uterine contraction,
  • bronchoconstriction. 
  • Vascular: vasoconstriction


Ductus Arteriosus

The "E" series of prostaglandins are responsible for maintaining the openness of the ductus arteriosus (by dilation of vascular smooth muscle) throughout the fetal period

Prostaglandin E2 (PGE2), produced by both the placenta and the DA itself, is the most potent of the E prostaglandins, but prostaglandin E1 (PGE1) also has a role in keeping the DA open


Misoprostil

  • Misoprostil is a synthetic analogue of prostaglandin E1
  • Uses: It is used for the prevention and treatment of non-steroidal anti-inlammatory induced ulcers.

Epoprostenol (prostacyclin – PGI2) - Epoprostenol is used to facilitate haemoiltration by continuous infusion into the extracorporeal circuit.

  • Epoprostenol causes inhibition of platelet adhesion and aggregation by stimulating adenylate cyclase

Carboprost is a synthetic prostaglandin analogue of PGF2.

  • It is used to treat postpartum haemorrhage resistant to treatment with oxytocin and ergometrine
  • Side effects include nausea and vomiting, flushing and bronchospasm. Cardiovascular collapse has been reported.

Platelets:

  • Platelets
  • Membrane-encapsulated fragments of megakaryocytes
  • Contain dense granules of:
  • ADP
  • ATP
  • Serotonin
  • Calcium
  • Magnesium
  • Can produce:
  • Nitric oxide
  • Prostaglandins
  • Thromboxane

PGE2 dilates afferent arterioles to maintain flow
